Michelin star rating analysis¶

By: Justin Kallungal¶

The Michelin Guide is a handbook that's purpose is to inform the common person of restaurants that are worth visiting. Nowadays, the Michelin star is a coveted feat that many restaurants aim to achieve, but is there a bias in how Michelin awards these stars? Are there genres of food that they show preference to over others? How about countries?¶
This tutorial aims to explore the trends in the food rating industry by taking a look at one of the most popular rating guides - The Michelin Guide. Throughout the tutorial, we will pose and answer questions in order to uncover meaning behind the data in the guide. The following datasets encompass the years 2018 and 2019.¶
Currently, the data only contains restaurant info in the following regions: ¶
Austria, California, Chicago, Croatia, Czech Republic, Denmark, Finland, Greece, Hong Kong, Hungary, Iceland, Macau, Norway, New York City, Poland, Ireland, Rio de Janeiro, Sao Paulo, South Korea, Singapore, Sweden, Taipei, Thailand, Washington DC, and United Kingdom¶
Explicitly not including these regions: Belgium, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Portugal, China, Spain, and Switzerland¶

So what are some quick abstractions from this map? For starters, it seems as though Western Europe hold the bulk of Michelin rated restaurants; specifically in the United Kingdom. The interesting thing to note here is that even though France is the origin of the Michelin Guide, these 3 data-sets do not include any of the datapoints within the country. Although this data excludes a few major countries (Belgium, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Portugal, China, Spain, and Switzerland), we are going to focus on the countries that do have representation to understand the sampling.

The interesting thing to find from this is that the data does not follow the distribution that we were expecting with regards to the overall graph. In actuality, Contemporary food dominates All of the Star categories. However, this distribution solely contains contemporary and asian genres. So we cannot say that California is typical of the rest of the countries' distributions.

Is the Michelin Guide truly accessible to the average consumer?¶

The main reason this guide exists is to recommend quality restaurants to the average consumer. Michelin argues that they filter out the ultra-expensive/exclusive restaurants as they are not accessible, but is that true? What dictates accessibility?¶
There are 5 categories of price, all represented by increasing amounts of '$'¶

Looking at a frequency of values that the one, two, and three star categories hold, we can see that the bulk of ratings are 3 Dollar signs and above. The Michelin Guide dictates that the Three Dollar sign rating means that the meal is between $25$-$50$ dollars per person for a meal. In 2013, Gallup states that the average income in the world was 9,733 dollars. Spending 25-50 on a meal is prohibitive to the average person. What is interesting is that the one dollar sign category is the lowest in both the one and two star ratings.

Hypothesis testing¶

Can we draw a correlation between the length of a restaurant's name and its price?¶
